description: From Middle English enteren, borrowed from Old French enterrer, enterer, from Vulgar Latin *interrāre (“to put in earth”).

verbs.description: inter (third-person singular simple present inters, present participle interring, simple past and past participle interred)

examples: Antonyms: dig up, disentomb, disinter, exhume, unearth

entries.meaning: To confine, as in a prison.
